  "narrative": {
    "intro": "Federal agencies obligated $474B in contract spending in FY2026 to date. The Department of Defense led obligations with $239B. Other large obligors included the Department of Homeland Security with $52B, the Department of Veterans Affairs with $51.1B, and the Department of Energy with $45.7B. Smaller but notable obligors in the top ten were the General Services Administration with $18.6B, the Department of Health and Human Services with $13.5B, and the National Aeronautics and Space Administration with $9.5B. The Department of Transportation, Department of Agriculture, and Department of Justice each recorded obligations of $8.7B, $6.3B, and $6.3B respectively. These figures reflect FY2026 to date federal contract obligations and use full contract values where provided.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "Which agencies account for the largest shares of federal contract obligations?",
        "body": "The Department of Defense is the largest obligor with $239B in contract obligations. The next-largest agencies are the Department of Homeland Security with $52B and the Department of Veterans Affairs with $51.1B. The Department of Energy follows with $45.7B, while the General Services Administration reported $18.6B."
      },
      {
        "heading": "How is contract spending distributed across other major civilian agencies?",
        "body": "Several civilian agencies reported multi-billion-dollar obligations: the Department of Health and Human Services with $13.5B, NASA with $9.5B, and the Department of Transportation with $8.7B. The Department of Agriculture and the Department of Justice each recorded $6.3B in obligations. These figures represent the FY2026 to date obligations by agency."
      }
    ]
  },
